Package: multpois
Title: Multinomial and Mixed Multinomial Analyses of Variance via the
    Multinomial-Poisson Trick
Version: 0.0.0.9100
Authors@R: 
    person("Jacob O.", "Wobbrock", 
           role = c("aut", "cre"),
           email = "wobbrock@uw.edu", 
           comment = c(ORCID = "0000-0003-3675-5491"))
Maintainer: Jacob O. Wobbrock <wobbrock@uw.edu>
Description: Dichotomous responses with two categories can be analyzed
    with 'glm' or 'lme4::glmer' using the 'family=binomial' parameter.
    Unfortunately, polytomous responses with three or more unordered
    categories cannot be analyzed similarly because there is no
    'family=multinomial' option. For between-subjects data,
    'nnet::multinom' can be used in place of 'glm', but this function
    cannot take random factors and therefore cannot handle within-subjects
    data (i.e., repeated measures). To address this issue, this package
    implements the multinomial-Poisson trick (Baker 1994, Chen & Kuo 2001,
    Guimaraes 2004, Lee et al. 2017), which transforms nominal response
    data into counts for each categorical alternative. These counts are
    then analyzed using 'glm' with 'family=poisson' for between-subjects
    data or 'lme4::glmer' with 'family=poisson' for within-subjects data.
    Omnibus analysis of variance results can be obtained along with post
    hoc pairwise comparisons.
